Greece has closed Banks, and stopped selling gold coins to the public after enforcing capital control. On June 27, 2015, the Greek government announced a shutdown of all
<a href="http://bullionexchanges.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/euro-373008_640.jpg"><img class=" size-medium wp-image-181 alignright" src="http://bullionexchanges.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/euro-373008_640-300x239.jpg" alt="euro-373008_640" width="300" height="239" /></a>banks in the country for at least ten days, stating they would re-open on July 6<sup>th</sup>. Gold rose on Monday amid the crisis but has since eased down.

Once re-opened withdrawals would be limited to 60 euros a day for each account with exemptions made for pension payments. The Athens stock exchange was also to be closed for a week, leaving both the people and investors in a state of unrest with a strong desire to move away from the euro.

This drastic decision has left investors searching for refuge, with the common view being that this was triggered by the turmoil of the Great recession. The demand for gold has risen fundamentally with gold futures climbing steadily.

GoldCore Ltd. has reported three times the average sales since the closing of banks and financial institutions in Greece. Bullion Vault a highly reputable internet peer-to-peer gold and silver bullion exchange with headquarters in the United Kingdom reported a jump in sales which is an indication of more extensive increments. Director of Frankfurt-based CoinInvest.com, states “When people learned that Greek banks will be closed, they started to think that it may not be a bad idea to have some money in gold.”

European nations are acting quickly, thus far for 2015 21.786 million ounces of silver American Eagles have been sold, 266,000 ounces of gold American Eagles have been purchased, while 95,000 gold American Buffalos have been purchased.

The impact is evident, but yields the opportunity for long term investments.

